A BITTER SOUTHERNER SUMMER READING ROUNDUP 2022 selection : Korean American: Food That Tastes Like Home by Eric Kim ( @ericjoonho ) While home looked like Atlanta for New York Times food writer Eric Kim, it often tasted like his parents‚Äô home country of Korea. His mother, Jean, prepared savory soups and stews, fall-apart-tender meat, and kimchi fried rice for the family. Kim spent a year of the COVID-19 pandemic writing personal stories and cooking alongside his mother in her Georgia kitchen. The result is Korean American, a cookbook fusion of her Korean sohn mat (translated literally to ‚Äúhand taste,‚Äù meaning one‚Äôs signature touch and the perfect way to express why one‚Äôs food never tastes as good as the originator‚Äôs recipe) and the techniques that he‚Äôs acquired as an American food writer. Vibrant photographs by Jenny Huang accompany recipes for dishes like Gochugaru Shrimp and Roasted Seaweed Grits and Pan-Seared Rib Eye With Gochujang Butter. https://bittersoutherner.com/features/2022/summer-reading-roundup List : @alisonlawatl Illustration : @marthaepark #summerreading #summerreadingroundup2022 #summerreadingroundup #supportindependentbookstores #bittersoutherner

The virus and its effects have been especially felt at the community level by families in South LA, many of whom were already disproportionately negatively impacted by decades of systemic disinvestment. There are also barriers to care faced by the South LA immigrant community, who may struggle to communicate due to language barriers or may not be eligible to receive certain public benefits. In conjunction with structural barriers, these factors contribute to a lack of accessibility to the healthcare system regardless of documentation status. We‚Äôve all heard that there are ‚Äògood cops‚Äô and ‚Äòbad cops‚Äô. How true is this, though? Let‚Äôs take a moment to consider the experience of Cariol Holloman-Horne, a retired Buffalo Police Officer who was betrayed by her fellow colleagues in blue (as well as the broken system) when she stood up for a suspect experiencing deadly force. Cariol Holloman-Horne was a Buffalo police officer from 1988 to 2008. According to the report, during a 2006 call to aid an officer in trouble, she arrived at a scene where a suspect was under arrest by Officer Gregory Kwiatowski. Officer Horne noticed that her colleague then began to chokehold the suspect. You might recall that a chokehold was the same technique that was employed during the killing of Eric Garner in Staten Island, New York City. When Officer Horne tried to remove Officer Kwiatkoski from this position, he let go of the suspect and responded by punching her in the face. The other officers at the scene closed ranks with Officer Kwiatkowski, alleging that she had endangered her fellow officer. An internal affairs investigation, however, found no wrongdoing on her behalf and offered her a four-day suspension. She did not accept this. Rather, she rejected this decision and in return, she was brought up on 13 departmental disciplinary charges. 11 stuck after a public hearing, and she was fired in 2008. From 2010 to 2021, Holloman-Horne fought the city of Buffalo for her pension to be reinstated. She finally won this right and has since become an advocate for police reform, as well as making ‚ÄúCariol‚Äôs Law‚Äù become the law across the country. It is a law that is supposed to ensure police officers face prosecution if they stand idle while a fellow officer uses excessive force, and protects them from retaliation by their fellow officers. History has taught us better, we don‚Äôt have any faith in this reform. When law enforcement officers take off their uniforms, they are just people with bias, intentions, and ideas. My public policy career launched when I was first appointed by former Governor Mark Dayton to sit on the nation's first ever Young Women's Cabinet in 2016. This cabinet advises the Governor on needed policies to ensure every young woman in the state of Minnesota has the opportunity to succeed and become the champion of their own life. In this role, I was elected to become co-chair, lead our annual legislative agenda, and receive appointment to the National Young Women's Advisory Council. IGNITE is one of the largest young women's political organizations dedicated to training the next generation of political leaders. After serving as the first female President of Chile and the first elected female leader in South America, @mbachelet was appointed the first executive director of the United Nations Entity for Gender Equality and the Empowerment of Women. Bachelet is a physician with an encyclopedic knowledge of military strategy, worked as the Health Minister and Defense Minister of Chile, and speaks English, German, French, and Portuguese, in addition to her native Spanish. She has broken an uncountable number of barriers. We are #BetterBecauseOfHer.

Tsai Ing-wen is the first female President of the Republic of China (Taiwan) and a member of the Taiwanese Democratic Progressive Party. She supports disadvantaged groups, favors LGBTQ+ rights, and champions bipartisanship, labor reform, and green energy. What can‚Äôt she do? Not only are the people of Taiwan #BetterBecauseOfHer ‚Äî we all are.

Not just anyone can be the youngest person ever awarded the Nobel Peace Prize. Malala Yousafzai is a human rights activist and a UN Messenger of Peace ‚Äî but these titles don‚Äôt do justice to the incredible work that Malala has done in her short life. Malala‚Äôs name is synonymous with inspiration ‚Äî her advocacy has evolved into an unstoppable international movement. ‚ÄúI tell my story not because it is unique,‚Äù says Malala, ‚Äúbut because it is the story of so many girls.‚Äù We are #BetterBecauseOfHer

The next person we want to highlight for Black History Month is Bessie Coleman! She was an American aviator and the first black woman in the world to earn a pilot's license. "Tell them that as soon as I can walk I'm going to fly!"

The next person we want to highlight for Black History Month is Ruby Bridges! Ruby Bridges was the first African American to attend an all-white public school at the age of six. Now, Bridges runs the Ruby Bridges Foundation to help troubled children at William Frantz and other schools & travels the country advocating the importance of education and integration to students.

Will you help us put Black Women First? As a member of HRSA's Black Women First initiative, we're working with Black women living with HIV and HIV service providers to create a new campaign designed to improve care and treatment coordination for Black women living with HIV, AND reduce HIV-related stigma. What can be done about the epidemic of violence facing Black women? First and foremost, is address the root causes of domestic violence, such as the objectification of women in media, rape culture, gender norms, the pay gap, and other forms of inequality. Thought the underlying causes of domestic violence are the same for all women ‚Äî they are often more pronounced for Black women. By directly combating these issues, we can reduce the incidence of domestic violence for all women ‚Äî and in particular, Black women who are even more impacted by these factors. For more information on Domestic Violence and Black women: https://www.google.com/url?q=https://www.blackburncenter.org/post/2020/02/26/black-women-domestic-violence&source=gmail-imap&ust=1644341218000000&usg=AOvVaw22-OIHC92UmwbcFwL3kK6h:=:https://www.blackburncenter.org/post/2020/02/26/black-women-domestic-violence #blackhistorymonth #women #health #wellness #domesticviolence #domesticviolenceawareness #2022

Angela Davis, a key figure in the U.S. civil rights movement, made significant contributions and influence in the fight for #RacialJustice, women's rights, and criminal justice reform. Through her activism and scholarship over the last decades, her work as an educator ‚Äî both at the university level and in the larger public sphere ‚Äî has always emphasized the importance of building communities of struggle for economic, racial, and gender justice. In recent years, her work has focused on the range of social problems associated with incarceration and the generalized criminalization of those communities most affected by poverty and racial discrimination, drawing on her own experiences in the early seventies as a person who spent eighteen months in jail and on trial, after being placed on the FBI‚Äôs ‚ÄúTen Most Wanted List.‚Äù Today, she continues to be an activist and lecturer as Professor Emeritus of History of Consciousness and Feminist Studies at the University of California at Santa Cruz. She is also a Distinguished Visiting Professor in the Women's and Gender Studies Department at Syracuse University. #BlackHerstoryMonth

In recognition of Holocaust Remembrance Day, we're sharing the incredible story of Irena Sendler, one of the great, unsung heroes of the WWII who led a secret operation that successfully smuggled 2,500 Jewish children out of the Warsaw Ghetto, saving them from almost certain death. To read her inspiring story, visit https://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=23101:=:http://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=23101 To share Irena Sendler's extraordinary story with children, we highly recommend "Irena's Jar of Secrets" for ages 6 to 10 (https://www.amightygirl.com/irena-s-jars-of-secrets:=:http://www.amightygirl.com/irena-s-jars-of-secrets), "Jars of Hope: How One Woman Helped Save 2,500 Children During the Holocaust" for ages 7 to 11 (https://www.amightygirl.com/jars-of-hope:=:http://www.amightygirl.com/jars-of-hope), and "Irena's Children: A True Story of Courage" for ages 10 to 14 (https://www.amightygirl.com/irena-s-children-young-readers:=:http://www.amightygirl.com/irena-s-children-young-readers) There is also a fascinating book about Sendler's life and the Kansas high school girls who helped bring her story to light: "Life in a Jar: The Irena Sendler Project" for ages 13 and up at https://www.amightygirl.com/life-in-a-jar-the-irena-sendler-project:=:http://www.amightygirl.com/life-in-a-jar For a gripping biography for adults about Irena Sendler's efforts to save the children of the Warsaw Ghetto, we recommend "Irena's Children" at https://www.amightygirl.com/irena-s-children:=:http://www.amightygirl.com/irena-s-children

Today marks the beginning of Holocaust Remembrance Week, the annual commemoration of the Holocaust. During this week -- and especially on Thursday's Holocaust Remembrance Day -- people around the world take time to remember everything that the Holocaust has to teach us: the evil that was done and the depths to which humanity can sink, but also the compassion, bravery, and goodness that emerges even in the darkest of times. It is a difficult topic for any of us, but particularly difficult to discuss with children. How do you talk about something so beyond most children‚Äôs comprehension in a way that respects the experience of those who lived it? To introduce children and teens to this dark chapter of human history and the lessons we all must learn from it, we've featured our favorite books about the Holocaust for young readers in our blog post, "60 Mighty Girl Books About The Holocaust." These books, from picture books to novels to memoirs, tackle this sensitive subject from a variety of perspectives with dignity, respect, and most importantly, hope. To read our blog post, "60 Mighty Girl Books About the Holocaust," visit https://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=11586:=:http://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=11586 For adult readers, we've shared many books about women living through WWII and the Holocaust in our blog post, "Telling Her Story: 40 Books for Adult Readers About Women Heroes of WWII," at https://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=24501:=:http://www.amightygirl.com/blog?p=24501 As always, if you purchase books that you discover on A Mighty Girl via the "Buy from Amazon" and other links found within this blog post and on every product page, we receive a small commission at no added cost to you, which allows us to maintain our website and continue to provide girl-empowering resources like this page for you as your own Mighty Girl grows. We appreciate your support! Reposted from A Mighty Girl

Today as many enjoy the day off, we want to uplift the reason we celebrate, and ask that you take action. While many Black people in the U.S have celebrated Juneteenth for 150+ years, only recently has awareness of this holiday reached the broader public, and become an official national holiday. This Juneteenth we are highlighting a petition circulated by our friends @sierraclub, urging President Biden to honor the Black community by designating Black Wall Street and the site of the 1908 Springfield Race Riot a national monuments. They write: ‚ÄúOur public lands must be representative of the diverse American experience. And yet, less than a quarter of our nation's national parks are currently dedicated to acknowledging the histories of Black and Indigenous peoples, movements, and cultures. This Juneteenth, President Biden should choose to honor the Black community by designating Black Wall Street and the site of the 1908 Springfield Race Riot as national monuments. It's time to confront our racist legacy and disrupt the status quo." https://act.sierraclub.org/actions/National?actionId=AR0362632:=:https://act.sierraclub.org/actions/National?actionId=AR0362632&id=70131000001Lp1FAAS You can find the petition link in our bio!

The federal holiday of Juneteenth National Independence Day will be celebrated Monday, June 20, in Massachusetts as it falls this year on a Sunday. The country‚Äôs newest holiday ‚Äì it was signed into law last year - is regarded as the oldest known celebration commemorating the end of slavery in the United States. It honors what happened on June 19, 1865, when Union Army Major General Gordon Granger arrived in Galveston, Texas with 2,000 federal troops, two months after the end of the Civil War, and read General Orders, No. 3, at different locations to officially inform ‚Äúthe people of Texas‚Äù that, ‚Äúin accordance with a proclamation from the Executive of the United States, all slaves are free.‚Äù The order referenced President Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs Emancipation Proclamation of January 1, 1863 that freed all slaves within ‚Äúany State or designated part of a State‚Äù where the people were ‚Äúin rebellion against the United States.‚Äù Texas was the last Confederate state where the proclamation, basically a temporary military decree, was enforced by Union forces arriving to take control of the state. Texas had approximately 200,000 slaves at the time and early reports of celebrations around ‚ÄúJuneteenth‚Äù referred to them as ‚Äútheir 4th of July.‚Äù Celebrations today include barbecues, the reading of the proclamation and discussions on further advancing racial equality in the country. The 13th amendment, abolishing slavery in the country as part of the Constitution, was passed by Congress on January 31, 1865, and ratified by the necessary three-fourths of the states by December 6, 1865.

Highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) strain H5N1 is a highly infectious, deadly virus that has killed or resulted in the death of more than 28 million birds. The virus has now been found in all four of the flyways across the United States. Around 26 states and more than 200 farms and backyard flocks have been impacted. If you have domestic outdoor birds, now is the time to implement your biosecurity protocols. This is particularly important if you live in a county or state where there are current avian influenza cases. Here are six tips to keep your flock safe. If you suffer even one positive case in your flock, your ENTIRE flock will be killed by state officials. The primary method for small backyard flocks is carbon dioxide gassing of birds. Keep your birds safe until the USDA and state officials give the all clear - which may be in June, when spring migrations have stopped. #avianinfluenza #hpai #h5n1 #chickens #turkeys #backyardchickens #vegan #veganism
